You can use a list comprehension to loop through the range of numbers and dynamically generate the `li` elements using React components.

Here's an example of how you can implement this:
```javascript
import React from'react';

function DynamicSlider() {
  const nums = Array.from({length: 20}, (v, k) => k + 1);

  return (
    <section className="dynamic-slider">
      {nums.map((num, index) => (
        <li key={index}>
          {num}
        </li>
      ))}
    </section>
  );
}
```
In this example, `Array.from` is used to create an array of numbers from `1` to `20`. The `map` function is then used to create a new array of `li` components.

Each `li` component will display its corresponding number from the `nums` array.

This is just one example of how you can dynamically generate `li` elements based on a range of numbers. You can adjust the range and formatting of the elements as needed.

